---
scope: src/fetch
description: Data-fetching orchestrator that gathers raw signals from npm registry, GitHub API, and OSV into a single result the scoring layer consumes
intent: >
  The fetch layer is the boundary between pkg-pulse and the outside world. Given a
  package name and an optional GitHub token, it retrieves every raw data source the
  scoring layer needs — packument, download counts, GitHub repo metadata, contributor
  stats, commit activity, vulnerability records, and deprecated-dependency status —
  and returns them as a single structured result where every field except the packument
  is nullable. The layer succeeds when it maximizes signal coverage under real-world
  constraints (rate limits, missing repos, transient failures) without letting any
  single source's failure prevent the others from completing.
outcomes:
  desired:
    - "The packument is always present in the result — it is the hard dependency that all other fetches derive from, and a missing packument is the only case that produces a hard failure"
    - "Every non-packument field in the result is T or null, never undefined — null means the fetch was attempted and the data was unavailable, giving downstream consumers an unambiguous signal to degrade"
    - "GitHub-dependent fetches are skipped entirely (resolved to null without a network call) when no GitHub repo coordinates can be extracted from the packument"
    - "A failure in any single parallel fetch does not cancel or delay the others — each settles independently"
    - "GitHub stats endpoints that return 202 (computing) are retried with backoff before degrading to null, so transient cache misses do not produce unnecessary signal gaps"
  undesired:
    - "A network error in one parallel fetch (e.g. OSV timeout) causes the entire fetch call to reject, losing all successfully fetched signals"
    - "GitHub calls are attempted when no repo coordinates exist, wasting rate-limited requests and producing confusing 404 nulls instead of clean skips"
    - "A 202 response from GitHub stats endpoints is treated as a final answer (null) on the first attempt without retrying, causing avoidable signal loss"
    - "The orchestrator catches and swallows the packument 404 instead of propagating it — the caller must distinguish 'package not found' from 'partial data'"
    - "Helper functions return undefined or throw inconsistently, forcing the orchestrator to handle both missing values and exceptions for the same logical case"
---

## Context

The fetch layer sits between the CLI entry point and the scoring engine. It owns all network I/O — no other layer in pkg-pulse makes HTTP calls. The scoring layer receives a fully-resolved result struct and never needs to know which APIs were called, in what order, or what failed. This boundary is load-bearing: if the fetch layer leaks partial state, throws unexpectedly, or conflates "not attempted" with "attempted and failed," the scoring layer cannot compute correct confidence indicators or normalize for missing signals.

The challenge is that the seven data sources have different reliability profiles. The npm registry packument is authoritative and nearly always available — a 404 there means the package genuinely does not exist. The npm downloads API is separate infrastructure and occasionally lags. GitHub REST endpoints are rate-limited (60 requests per hour unauthenticated, 5,000 with a token) and two of the stats endpoints (contributors, commit activity) use a deferred-computation model that returns HTTP 202 when results are not cached. The OSV vulnerability database is a free public API with no authentication but occasional timeouts. Direct-dependency deprecation checks require one packument fetch per dependency, which can mean dozens of additional registry calls for dependency-heavy packages.

These varying failure modes mean the fetch layer cannot treat all sources uniformly. The packument is a hard prerequisite — without it, there is no version number for OSV, no repository URL for GitHub, and no dependency list for deprecation checks. Everything else is best-effort. The orchestration pattern (sequential prerequisite, then parallel fan-out with independent settlement) exists to maximize the data delivered to scoring while minimizing wall-clock time and ensuring that one slow or failing source never blocks the rest.

## Strategy

**Sequential packument, then parallel fan-out.** The packument must resolve first because it provides three pieces of data that downstream fetches depend on: the latest version tag (needed by the vulnerability query), the repository URL (needed to derive GitHub owner/repo coordinates), and the dependency list (needed to check each direct dep for deprecation). Once the packument resolves, all remaining fetches launch concurrently.

**T-or-null return contract on every non-packument field.** Each helper function returns its domain type on success or null when the data is unavailable. The orchestrator wraps every parallel call in a settlement boundary so that a rejected promise (network error, unexpected status code) is mapped to null, identical to an intentional skip. Downstream consumers never see undefined and never need to catch — the null contract is the only degradation signal.

**GitHub calls gated on repo coordinate extraction.** Before launching any GitHub fetch, the orchestrator runs a pure extraction step against the packument's repository field. If extraction returns null (no repo field, non-GitHub host, unparseable URL), all three GitHub fetches resolve to null immediately without making a network call. This avoids wasting rate-limited GitHub requests on packages that have no GitHub presence.

**202 retry with bounded attempts for GitHub stats endpoints.** The contributor stats and commit activity endpoints use GitHub's deferred-computation model: the first request to an uncached repo returns HTTP 202 with an empty body. The fetch helpers retry up to three times with a one-second delay between attempts. If the endpoint still returns 202 after all retries, the helper returns null — the data is genuinely unavailable on this call, and the scoring layer will normalize around it.

**Graceful handling of rate limits and access errors.** GitHub 403 (rate limited) and 404 (private repo, deleted repo) both map to null. The helper does not distinguish between them because the scoring layer treats both the same way: the signal is unavailable. The distinction is only relevant for user-facing messaging, which the output layer handles based on whether a GitHub token was provided.

**Parallel deprecation checks reusing the packument fetcher.** Each direct dependency triggers its own packument fetch to check for the deprecated field on its latest version. These are fired in parallel with independent settlement. A dependency whose packument cannot be fetched (private, deleted, network error) is treated as non-deprecated — the conservative choice that avoids false positives.

**Scoped package URL encoding.** Both the npm registry and downloads APIs require scoped package names to be percent-encoded (the @ becomes %40 and the / becomes %2F). Each helper that constructs a registry or downloads URL handles this encoding internally so the orchestrator passes raw package names without transformation.

## Good examples

A complete result with all signals available (authenticated GitHub, OSV responsive, no deprecated deps):

```
FetchResult {
  packument:            full packument object (never null)
  downloads:            { lastWeek: { downloads: 2100000 }, lastMonth: { downloads: 8400000 } }
  githubRepo:           { archived: false, pushed_at: "2026-03-15T...", open_issues_count: 42, ... }
  githubContributors:   [ { author: { login: "..." }, total: 340, weeks: [...] }, ... ]
  githubCommitActivity: [ { total: 12, week: 1710720000, days: [...] }, ... ]
  vulnerabilities:      []
  deprecatedDeps:       []
}
```

A degraded result for a package with no GitHub repo and an OSV timeout:

```
FetchResult {
  packument:            full packument object
  downloads:            { lastWeek: { downloads: 340 }, lastMonth: { downloads: 1200 } }
  githubRepo:           null   (no repo coordinates — skipped, not failed)
  githubContributors:   null   (no repo coordinates — skipped)
  githubCommitActivity: null   (no repo coordinates — skipped)
  vulnerabilities:      null   (OSV timed out — attempted and failed)
  deprecatedDeps:       [ { name: "old-util", deprecated: "Use new-util instead" } ]
}
```

Both results are valid inputs to the scoring layer. The scoring layer uses the null fields to compute signal coverage and re-weight the aggregate.

## Bad examples

**Undefined instead of null for a failed fetch:**

```
FetchResult {
  ...
  vulnerabilities: undefined   // Wrong: contract requires null, not undefined
}
```

The scoring layer checks `field === null` to detect unavailable signals. An undefined value slips through that check and may be treated as "signal present but empty," producing a confident score from incomplete data.

**GitHub calls attempted when no repo coordinates exist:**

```
// extractRepoUrl returned null, but the orchestrator still calls:
fetchGithubRepo("", "", token)  // 404, wastes a rate-limited request
```

This burns one of the 60 unauthenticated requests per hour on a call that will always fail, and produces a null that is indistinguishable from a genuine rate-limit or private-repo null. The orchestrator must skip the call entirely when coordinates are absent.

**Packument 404 caught and mapped to null instead of thrown:**

```
FetchResult {
  packument: null   // Wrong: packument must never be null
  ...
}
```

If the packument is null, the scoring layer has no version, no dependency list, no repository URL — it cannot score anything. A packument 404 must propagate as an exception so the CLI can report "package not found" and exit non-zero.

**Single Promise.all instead of Promise.allSettled:**

If any one fetch rejects, Promise.all rejects the entire group, discarding all fulfilled results. A five-second OSV timeout would throw away a perfectly good GitHub response, download counts, and deprecation check results. The settlement boundary is what makes partial coverage possible.

